snippet.description:
In July 1969, the crew of the Apollo 11 was preparing for the United States' first attempt of landing men on the moon. In just 9 years, the country has gone from Space amateur to technological hyperpower. This is a story of how the Cold War paranoia and an incredible expenditure paid off.

persons.role: President of the United States

basics.eventDescription: On September 12, 1962, President John F. Kennedy delivered a speech at Rice University, reiterating the United States' commitment to space exploration and rallying public support for the Apollo program. He famously declared, 'We choose to go to the Moon in this decade and do the other things, not because they are easy, but because they are hard.'

persons.role: Vice President
President of the United States

basics.eventDescription: On November 22, 1963, President John F. Kennedy was assassinated while riding in a motorcade in Dealey Plaza, Dallas, Texas. The assassination of the 35th President of the United States marked a tragic and pivotal moment in American history. The event sparked investigations, conspiracy theories, and a profound sense of loss among the American people. ice President Lyndon B. Johnson automatically succeeded to the presidency, making him the 36th President of the United States. Johnson assumed the presidency immediately and started to complete the remainder of Kennedy's presidency.

basics.eventDescription: A ticker-tape parade was held in New York City on August 13, 1969, to honor the Apollo 11 astronauts. Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin, and Michael Collins rode in open cars through the streets of Manhattan, greeted by cheering crowds.

persons.role: American astronaut, first person to walk on the Moon

basics.eventDescription: Neil Armstrong became the first person to set foot on the lunar surface on July 20, 1969, uttering the famous words, 'That's one small step for [a] man, one giant leap for mankind.'
basics.eventName: First person to set foot on the Moon

basics.eventDescription: On October 4, 1957, the Soviet Union launched Sputnik 1, the world's first artificial satellite. This historic event marked the beginning of the space age and initiated the Space Race between the United States and the Soviet Union.

On April 12, 1961, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first human to orbit the Earth aboard the Vostok 1 spacecraft. Gagarin's successful spaceflight demonstrated Soviet space capabilities and added to the intensifying competition between superpowers.
basics.eventName: Soviet cosmonaut first human to orbit Earth

persons.role: President of the United States

basics.eventDescription: On May 25, 1961, President John F. Kennedy delivered a speech before a joint session of the United States Congress, in which he set forth the ambitious goal of sending an American astronaut to the Moon and returning them safely to Earth before the end of the decade. This announcement marked the beginning of the Apollo program, a historic effort to achieve human space exploration beyond Earth's orbit.

On June 16, 1963, Soviet cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova became the first woman to travel to space aboard the Vostok 6 spacecraft. Her mission highlighted Soviet achievements in space exploration and inspired discussions about the role of women in space.
basics.eventName: Soviet cosmonaut first woman to travel to space

basics.eventDescription: The Apollo 11 Command Module, named 'Columbia,' re-entered Earth's atmosphere and splashed down safely in the Pacific Ocean on July 24, 1969. The mission was a historic success, marking the first time humans had landed on the Moon and returned safely to Earth.
basics.eventName: Command Module splashed down safely in the Pacific

basics.eventName: Lunar Module successfully landed on the Moon
basics.eventDescription: The Lunar Module successfully landed on the Moon on July 20, 1969. This remarkable technical achievement required precise navigation and control, overcoming the challenges of lunar terrain and ensuring a safe landing for astronauts Neil Armstrong and Edwin 'Buzz' Aldrin.

persons.role: American astronaut, first person to walk on the Moon
American astronaut, joined Armstrong on the Moon's surface

basics.eventDescription: After spending approximately 21 hours on the lunar surface, Armstrong and Aldrin returned to the Lunar Module, which successfully ascended to rejoin the Command Module. The crew then began their journey back to Earth.
basics.eventName: Astronauts return to the Lunar Module

basics.eventDescription: Apollo 11 astronauts Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin, and Michael Collins were released from quarantine from LRL (Lunar Receiving Laboratory) on August 13, 1969, after their return from the Moon. They were quarantined to prevent any potential lunar pathogens from spreading to Earth.

The Nuremberg Military Tribunals occurred after the Nuremberg trials, held by the International Military Tribunal, which concluded in October 1946.

basics.eventDescription: Members from both parties highlight the potential scientific and technological advancements that could result from the Apollo program. They discuss the long-term benefits to various industries and the economy.

On January 27, 1967, tragedy struck during a pre-launch test for Apollo 1 when a cabin fire resulted in the deaths of astronauts Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger B. Chaffee. This devastating event highlighted the technical challenges and risks involved in the Apollo program and led to significant safety improvements in subsequent missions.

basics.eventName: SBF starts to exploit the crypto trading discrepencies between USA and Japan.
basics.eventDescription: In January 2018, Bankman-Fried organized an arbitrage trade, moving up to $25 million per day, to take advantage of the higher price of bitcoin in Japan compared to the United States. After attending a late 2018 cryptocurrency conference in Macau, he moved to Hong Kong
